3732 // <e> NRFX_PWM_NRF52_ANOMALY_109_WORKAROUND_ENABLED - Enables nRF52 Anomaly 109 workaround for PWM.
3733 
3734 // <i> The workaround uses interrupts to wake up the CPU and ensure
3735 // <i> it is active when PWM is about to start a DMA transfer. For
3736 // <i> initial transfer, done when a playback is started via PPI,
3737 // <i> a specific EGU instance is used to generate the interrupt.
3738 // <i> During the playback, the PWM interrupt triggered on SEQEND
3739 // <i> event of a preceding sequence is used to protect the transfer
3740 // <i> done for the next sequence to be played.

4320 // <i> a start event of zero-length transmission to start the clock. This

4322 // <i> that the proper transfer will be started. See more in the Errata
4323 // <i> document or Anomaly 109 Addendum located at

4438 // <q> NRFX_SPIS_NRF52_ANOMALY_109_WORKAROUND_ENABLED - Enables nRF52 Anomaly 109 workaround for SPIS.
4439 
4440 
4441 // <i> The workaround uses a GPIOTE channel to generate interrupts
4442 // <i> on falling edges detected on the CSN line. This will make
4443 // <i> the CPU active for the moment when SPIS starts DMA transfers,
4444 // <i> and this way the transfers will be protected.
4445 // <i> This workaround uses GPIOTE driver, so this driver must be
4446 // <i> enabled as well.
4447

Normally, during initialization driver tries to clear all registers to known state before doing the initialization itself. This gives initialization safe procedure, no matter when it would be called. If you activate TWIS only once and do never uninitialize it - set this flag to 1 what gives more optimal code.

7188 // <e> FDS_ENABLED - fds - Flash data storage module
7189 //==========================================================
7190 #ifndef FDS_ENABLED
7191 #define FDS_ENABLED 0
7192 #endif
7193 // <h> Pages - Virtual page settings
7194 
7195 // <i> Configure the number of virtual pages to use and their size.
7196 //==========================================================
7197 // <o> FDS_VIRTUAL_PAGES - Number of virtual flash pages to use.
7198 // <i> One of the virtual pages is reserved by the system for garbage collection.
7199 // <i> Therefore, the minimum is two virtual pages: one page to store data and one page to be used by the system for garbage collection.
7200 // <i> The total amount of flash memory that is used by FDS amounts to @ref FDS_VIRTUAL_PAGES * @ref FDS_VIRTUAL_PAGE_SIZE * 4 bytes.
7201 
7202 #ifndef FDS_VIRTUAL_PAGES
7203 #define FDS_VIRTUAL_PAGES 3
7204 #endif
7205 
7206 // <o> FDS_VIRTUAL_PAGE_SIZE - The size of a virtual flash page.
7207 
7208 
7209 // <i> Expressed in number of 4-byte words.
7210 // <i> By default, a virtual page is the same size as a physical page.
7211 // <i> The size of a virtual page must be a multiple of the size of a physical page.
7212 // <1024=> 1024
7213 // <2048=> 2048
7214

7216 #define FDS_VIRTUAL_PAGE_SIZE 1024
7217 #endif

7258

7260 // <i> Records with an incorrect CRC can still be 'seen' by the user using FDS functions, but they cannot be opened.
7261 // <i> Additionally, they will not be garbage collected until they are deleted.
7262 //==========================================================

7264 #define FDS_CRC_CHECK_ON_READ 0
7265 #endif

7267 
7268

7272 // <0=> Disabled
7273

7757 #endif

7760 // <i> Increase this value if events frequently return the @ref NRF_ERROR_TIMEOUT error.
7761 // <i> The SoftDevice might fail to schedule flash access due to high BLE activity.

7768 // <i> This value must be a multiple of four.
7769 // <i> Lowering this value can increase the chances of the SoftDevice being able to execute flash operations in between radio activity.
7770 // <i> This value is bound by the maximum number of bytes that can be written to flash in a single call to @ref sd_flash_write.
7771 // <i> That is 1024 bytes for nRF51 ICs and 4096 bytes for nRF52 ICs.
7772 
7773 #ifndef NRF_FSTORAGE_SD_MAX_WRITE_SIZE
7774 #define NRF_FSTORAGE_SD_MAX_WRITE_SIZE 4096
7775 #endif

8271 
8272 //==========================================================
8273 // <o> NRF_LOG_MSGPOOL_ELEMENT_SIZE - Size of a single element in the pool of memory objects.
8274 // <i> If a small value is set, then performance of logs processing
8275 // <i> is degraded because data is fragmented. Bigger value impacts
8276 // <i> RAM memory utilization. The size is set to fit a message with
8277 // <i> a timestamp and up to 2 arguments in a single memory object.

8283 // <o> NRF_LOG_MSGPOOL_ELEMENT_COUNT - Number of elements in the pool of memory objects
8284 // <i> If a small value is set, then it may lead to a deadlock
8285 // <i> in certain cases if backend has high latency and holds
8286 // <i> multiple messages for long time. Bigger value impacts
8287 // <i> RAM memory usage.
8288 
8289 #ifndef NRF_LOG_MSGPOOL_ELEMENT_COUNT
8290 #define NRF_LOG_MSGPOOL_ELEMENT_COUNT 8

12731 // <h> Dispatch model
12732 
12733 // <i> This setting configures how Stack events are dispatched to the application.
12734 //==========================================================
12735 // <o> NRF_SDH_DISPATCH_MODEL
12736 
12737 
12738 // <i> NRF_SDH_DISPATCH_MODEL_INTERRUPT: SoftDevice events are passed to the application from the interrupt context.
12739 // <i> NRF_SDH_DISPATCH_MODEL_APPSH: SoftDevice events are scheduled using @ref app_scheduler.
12740 // <i> NRF_SDH_DISPATCH_MODEL_POLLING: SoftDevice events are to be fetched manually.
12741 // <0=> NRF_SDH_DISPATCH_MODEL_INTERRUPT
12742 // <1=> NRF_SDH_DISPATCH_MODEL_APPSH
12743 // <2=> NRF_SDH_DISPATCH_MODEL_POLLING
12744 
12745 #ifndef NRF_SDH_DISPATCH_MODEL
12746 #define NRF_SDH_DISPATCH_MODEL 0
12747 #endif
